Dataset: Video Game Sales by Anand Shaw, Kaggle.com

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/anandshaw2001/video-game-sales

library(tidyverse)
sales_df <- read_csv(file = "vgsales.csv")
sales_df

1 Exploratory Data Analysis

1.1 Data Description

This dataset describes video game sales across platforms, genres, and regions.

1.2 Key Concepts in Statistics

Assume data is population for only this section. You might need to change this section depending on what you plan to research in Section 2.

  1. What is the population? Check Section 2 for this.

All video game sales across platforms, genres, and regions.

  1. What is the sample? Check Section 2 for this.

Video game sales from more than 16,500 games

  • Platform: Categorical

2 Probability Distributions

Assume the data uploaded is population data in this subsection only.

2.1 Qualitative Data

Select one qualitative variable and use one level of the qualitative variable as success.

Selected Variable: Genre Success: Genre = Puzzle

  1. Show the number of successes is from binomial distribution. P(X)
  • There is a fixed number of observations (n = 16598)
  • Each trial is independent
  • Only two outcomes (Genre = Puzzle or Genre \(\ne\) Puzzle)
n <- 16598
x <- sales_df %>% filter(Genre == "Puzzle") %>% pull(Genre) %>% length

p <- x/n
p
## [1] 0.03506447
  1. Find the probability the random variable is more than its mean. P(X > 582)
1 - pbinom(q = 581, size = n, prob = p)
## [1] 0.5058083
  1. Find the sampling distribution of the sample proportion of the qualitative variable with a sample size of at least 50 (this number might need to change to satisfy the requirement).

Mean

p
## [1] 0.03506447

Standard Deviation

sqrt(p * (1- p)/n)
## [1] 0.001427759

Shape

Shape = approx. normal

n*p*(1 - p) >= 10
## [1] TRUE
puzzles_pmf <- tibble(x = 0:1000, #Applying cutoff at x = 1000 for better visualization, the odds beyond 1000 or essentially 0
                      p_x = dpois(x = 0:1000, lambda = 582)) 
puzzles_pmf %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = p_x)) +
  geom_col(color = "blue")

puzzles_pmf

3 One Sample: Confidence Interval and Hypothesis Testing

Assume full data is a sample for this section.

Section 3.1 Confidence interval

  1. Find the point estimate and 98% confidence interval for the population proportion from the variable selected in Section 2.1 part a).

Point Estimate

#Point Estimate
p_hat <- p
p_hat
## [1] 0.03506447

Check Requirements 1) n <= 0.05 N 2) Simple random sample (assume yes) 3) n p_hat (1-p_hat) >= 10

n* p_hat* ((1-p_hat)) >= 10
## [1] TRUE

Construct and Interpret Confidence Interval

prop.test(x = 582, n = 16598, conf.level = 0.98)
## 
##  1-sample proportions test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  582 out of 16598, null probability 0.5
## X-squared = 14350, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true p is not equal to 0.5
## 98 percent confidence interval:
##  0.03186289 0.03857188
## sample estimates:
##          p 
## 0.03506447

We are 98% confident that proportion of video games with the genre of Puzzle is between 0.03186289 and 0.03857188

  1. Find the point estimate and 99% confidence interval for the population mean from the variable selected in Section 2.1 part b).

Point Estimate

mean(sales)
## [1] 0.07778166

Check Requirements 1) n <= 0.05 N 2) Simple random sample 3) n >= 30 or X ~ Normal

n >= 30
## [1] TRUE

Construct and Interpret Confidence Interval

t.test(x = sales_df %>% pull(JP_Sales), conf.level = 0.99)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sales_df %>% pull(JP_Sales)
## t = 32.399, df = 16597, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 99 percent confidence interval:
##  0.07159714 0.08396618
## sample estimates:
##  mean of x 
## 0.07778166

We are 99% confident that the population mean for video games with the genre Puzzle is between 0.07159714 and 0.08396618

Section 3.2 One sample proportion hypothesis testing

Formulate a research question to conduct a one-sample proportion hypothesis test based on the variable from section 2.1.

  1. State your research question. Testing if the proportion of video games in the genre Puzzle is greater than 4% this year at alpha level = 0.01?

  2. Conduction hypothesis test.

Step 1: State the hypotheses

\(H_0: p = .04\)

\(H_A: p > .04\)

Step 2: What is the level of significance, \(\alpha\)?

$= 0.01 $

Step 0: Check requirement

  • n \(\le\) 0.05N (independent samples)
  • Simple random sample
  • $np_0(1-p_0) $
n* p* ((1-p)) >= 10
## [1] TRUE

Step 3: Calculate test statistics and p-value.

n <- sales_df %>% pull(Genre) %>% length()
x <- sales_df %>% filter(Genre == "Puzzle") %>% pull(Genre) %>% length
n
## [1] 16598
z_0 <- (x/n - 0.04)/ (sqrt(0.04 * (1-0.04)/n))
z_0
## [1] -3.244864
prop.test(x = 582, n = 16598, p = 0.04, alternative = "greater", correct = F)
## 
##  1-sample proportions test without continuity correction
## 
## data:  582 out of 16598, null probability 0.04
## X-squared = 10.529, df = 1, p-value = 0.9994
## alternative hypothesis: true p is greater than 0.04
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.03279075 1.00000000
## sample estimates:
##          p 
## 0.03506447

Step 4: Decision Since p-value = 0.9994 and is greater than alpha level 0.01, we fail to reject H_0

Step 5: Conclusion There is insufficient evidence at alpha level = 0.01 that the proportion of video games with the genre Puzzle is greater than 4%.

Section 3.2 One sample mean (t test) hypothesis testing

Formulate a research question to conduct a one sample t test hypothesis test based on the variable in section 2.2.

The mean of Japanese sales for video games is greater than 80,000 dollars (our dataset uses decimals for millions, so it would be .5) at alpha = 0.05

Step 1: State the hypotheses

$H_0: = 80,000 $

$H_A: > 80,000 $

Step 2: What is the level of significance, \(\alpha\)?

$= 0.05 $

Step 0: Check requirement

  • n \(\le\) 0.05N (independent samples)
  • Simple random sample
  • n \(\ge\) 30 or X Normal

Step 3: Calculate test statistics and p-value.

sales <- sales_df %>% pull(JP_Sales)
t.test(sales, mu = .08, alternative = "greater")
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sales
## t = -0.92404, df = 16597, p-value = 0.8223
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is greater than 0.08
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.07383263        Inf
## sample estimates:
##  mean of x 
## 0.07778166

Step 4: Decision Since p-value = 0.8223 > 0.05, we fail to reject H_0: $= 80,000 $

Step 5: Conclusion There is insufficient evidence at \(\alpha = 0.05\) that the mean of JP sales for video games is greater than 80,000 dollars.

4 Two Samples t-test : Independent Sampling Method.

Create a research question to perform a two-sample mean (independent t-test) hypothesis test using the variables you chose in section 2.

  1. Create the research question.

Is the mean value of video game sales greater in North America than in Japan at a 0.05 significance level?

b)Run a hypothesis test to test your hypothesis.

Step 1: State the hypotheses

\(H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2\)

\(H_A: \mu_1 > \mu_2\)

Step 2: What is the level of significance, \(\alpha\)?

\(\alpha = 0.05\)

Step 0: Check requirement

  • n1 <= 0.05N1 and n2 <= 0.05N2
  • Simple Random Samples
  • n1 >= 30, n2 >= 30
n1 <- sales_df %>% pull(NA_Sales) %>% length()
n2 <- sales_df %>% pull(JP_Sales) %>% length()
n1 >= 30
## [1] TRUE
n2 >= 30
## [1] TRUE

Step 3: Calculate test statistics and p-value.

t.test(x = sales_df %>% pull(NA_Sales), y = sales_df %>% pull(JP_Sales), mu = 0, alternative = "greater", var.equal = F)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sales_df %>% pull(NA_Sales) and sales_df %>% pull(JP_Sales)
## t = 27.571, df = 21262, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1757357       Inf
## sample estimates:
##  mean of x  mean of y 
## 0.26466743 0.07778166

Step 4: Decision

Since p-value = 2.2e-16 < 0.05, reject \(H_0\)

Step 5: Conclusion

There is sufficient evidence at \(\alpha = 0.05\) to conclude that the average video game sales in NA is higher than in JP

  1. Use the Confidence interval to test your hypothesis. Step 1: State the hypotheses

\(H_0: \mu_d = 0\)

\(H_A: \mu_d < 0\)

Step 2: Construct Confidence Interval

t.test(x = sales_df %>% pull(NA_Sales), y = sales_df %>% pull(JP_Sales), conf.level = 0.90)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  sales_df %>% pull(NA_Sales) and sales_df %>% pull(JP_Sales)
## t = 27.571, df = 21262, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 90 percent confidence interval:
##  0.1757357 0.1980358
## sample estimates:
##  mean of x  mean of y 
## 0.26466743 0.07778166

Step 3: Decision

Since p-value = 2.2e-16 < 0.05, reject \(H_0\)

Step 4: Conclusion

There is sufficient evidence at \(\alpha = 0.05\) to conclude that the average video game sales in NA is higher than in JP

5 Simple Linear regression

Use two quantitative variables to show if there is a linear relationship between them. Is there a linear relationship between video game sales in North America and sales in Japan?

Step 1: State the hypotheses

\(H_0: \beta = 0\)

\(H_A: \beta \neq 0\)

Step 2: What is the level of significance, \(\alpha\)?

$= 0.01 $

Step 0: Check requirement

  • SRS
  • Resid ~Normal
na_sales <- sales_df %>% pull(NA_Sales)
jp_sales <- sales_df %>% pull(JP_Sales)
#Draws line
sales_df %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = na_sales, y = jp_sales)) +
  geom_point(color = "coral") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Step 3: Calculate test statistics and p-value.

sales_mod <- lm(formula = jp_sales ~ na_sales, data = sales_df)
sales_mod %>% summary()
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = jp_sales ~ na_sales, data = sales_df)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -4.3400 -0.0634 -0.0412 -0.0127  8.2676 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 0.032698   0.002254   14.51   <2e-16 ***
## na_sales    0.170342   0.002626   64.88   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.2762 on 16596 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2023, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2023 
## F-statistic:  4209 on 1 and 16596 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

p-value = 0

Step 4: Decision Since p-value = 0, which is less than alpha = 0.01, we reject H_0

Step 5: Conclusion There is sufficient evidence at alpha = 0.01 that there is a linear relationship between video game sales in North America and Japan.

6: Report

Section 1.3: Most sales for North America and Japan are around 0. The most amount of games sold by genre is action games and the platform that is sold to the most is the PS2 and the DS.

Section 3: With a 98% confidence interval, the proportion of puzzle video games in our dataset is between 0.03186289 and 0.03857188. We are 99% confident that the population mean for video games with the genre Puzzle is between 0.07159714 and 0.08396618

One sample proportion hypothesis testing: Hypothesis: Testing if the proportion of video games in the genre Puzzle is greater than 4% this year at alpha level = 0.01? Conclusion: With our one sample proportion hypothesis testing. At alpha = 0.01, there is insufficient evidence that the proportion of video games with the genre Puzzle is greater than 4%, which is also validated by our 98% proportion confidence interval.

One sample mean (t test) hypothesis testing: Hypothesis: The mean of Japanese sales for video games is greater than 80,000 dollars (our dataset uses decimals for millions, so it would be .5) at alpha = 0.05 Conclusion: There is insufficient evidence at \(\alpha = 0.05\) that the mean of JP sales for video games is greater than 80,000 dollars.

Section 4: Independent Sampling Method: Hypothesis: Is the mean value of video game sales greater in North America than in Japan at a 0.05 significance level? Conclusion: There is sufficient evidence at \(\alpha = 0.05\) to conclude that the average video game sales in NA is higher than in JP

Confidence interval to test hypothesis (conclusion): There is sufficient evidence at \(\alpha = 0.05\) to conclude that the average video game sales in NA is higher than in JP

Section 5: Simple Linear Regression: Hypothesis: Is there a linear relationship between video game sales in North America and sales in Japan? Conclusion: There is sufficient evidence at \(\alpha = 0.01\) that there is a linear relationship between video game sales in North America and Japan.
